  "rationale": "Strategy B is what main.py runs by default and what produced output.csv. Strategy A spends roughly one model call per claim and accepts the first answer regardless of confidence; B spends more calls only on claims the model itself flags as uncertain (confidence 0.4-0.75) or visually suspect (claim_mismatch / wrong_object / possible_manipulation / non_original_image), and routes genuine two-pass disagreement to a stronger tie-breaker model rather than guessing. The cost delta (see avg_calls_per_claim above) is small because escalation is rare by construction -- it only fires on actual disagreement, not on every borderline case.",
